docs.abstract: The neighborhood literary hangout, once struggling, appears to be winning over young readers who enjoy the face-to-face social experience of shopping for “real books.”
docs.snippet: The neighborhood literary hangout, once struggling, appears to be winning over young readers who enjoy the face-to-face social experience of shopping for “real books.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The decades of trauma suffered by independent neighborhood bookstores — damage from bargain megastores, the ascension of the e-book and Amazon’s flash delivery of cut-rate reading — hardly hindered Chris Doeblin’s search for the right place to open his fourth independent bookstore in Manhattan.

headline.main: Indie Bookstores Are Back, With a Passion
headline.print_headline: Indie Bookstores Are Back, With a Passion

docs.abstract: The agreement would let businesses like Google and Facebook continue to move personal data across the Atlantic, but European privacy officials may balk.
docs.snippet: The agreement would let businesses like Google and Facebook continue to move personal data across the Atlantic, but European privacy officials may balk.
docs.lead_paragraph: European officials on Tuesday agreed to a deal with the United States that would let Google, Amazon and thousands of other businesses continue moving people’s digital data, including social media posts and financial information, back and forth across the Atlantic.

headline.main: U.S. and Europe in ‘Safe Harbor’ Data Deal, but Legal Fight May Await
headline.print_headline: Deal Struck to Balance U.S.-Europe Data Fears

docs.abstract: As the stock market continues its 2016 slide, technology stocks are falling even further, victims partly of their own success.
docs.snippet: As the stock market continues its 2016 slide, technology stocks are falling even further, victims partly of their own success.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — As the United States economy muddled along over the last few years, investors paid handsome sums to get in on high-flying technology companies that were among the few pockets of steady growth. Now comes the payback.

headline.main: Tech Stocks Have Fallen Faster and Further Than Broader Market
headline.print_headline: Tech Stocks Drop Faster  and Further Than Average

docs.abstract: Yahoo and Twitter are just the latest tech companies shaping plans for major overhauls and management shake-ups. A look back at how Priceline, Amazon and eBay weathered turbulent times.
docs.snippet: Yahoo and Twitter are just the latest tech companies shaping plans for major overhauls and management shake-ups. A look back at how Priceline, Amazon and eBay weathered turbulent times.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ups and downs are nothing new in the fast-moving technology industry. And as soon as a company hits turbulence, calls for a management shake-up almost always follow.

headline.main: Tech’s Track Record of Shake-Ups at the Top

docs.abstract: A day after saying that Amazon planned to open 300 to 400 brick-and-mortar bookstores, a shopping mall executive stepped back from his comments.
docs.snippet: A day after saying that Amazon planned to open 300 to 400 brick-and-mortar bookstores, a shopping mall executive stepped back from his comments.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — A day after saying that Amazon plans to open hundreds of physical bookstores, the chief executive of a large shopping mall operator has backed away from the comments.

headline.main: Mall Executive Backtracks From Statement on Amazon Retail Stores

docs.abstract: Furla lets you get personal, Apiece Apart and Dieppa Restrepo are teaming up on a sample sale, and more.
docs.snippet: Furla lets you get personal, Apiece Apart and Dieppa Restrepo are teaming up on a sample sale, and more.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Thursday, Amazon Fashion will unveil a shopping destination featuring the spring collections of the 2015 CFDA/Vogue Fashion Fund contenders just in time for “The Fashion Fund” Series 3 premiere on the Internet retailer’s streaming service. You’ll find sweet picks like a Jonathan Simkhai radial gingham dress ($445), Brother Vellies ankle-strap sandals ($435) and a Gypsy Sport mixed media cap ($132) from the three winners, and items from all of the remaining seven finalists. At amazon.com/FashionFundShop.

headline.main: Amazon Puts Spotlight on ‘The Fashion Fund’
headline.print_headline: Amazon Puts Spotlight on ‘The Fashion Fund’

docs.abstract: How an offhand remark about Amazon opening new bookstores spawned a viral reaction and a backtracking.
docs.snippet: How an offhand remark about Amazon opening new bookstores spawned a viral reaction and a backtracking.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon is poised to expand its one Seattle bookstore into a chain of such stores. Or is it?

headline.main: Daily Report: The Mystery of Amazon’s Bookstores

docs.abstract: Delivery services now come through in hours, not days. But the boxes after boxes generated create environmental concerns, and some guilt.
docs.snippet: Delivery services now come through in hours, not days. But the boxes after boxes generated create environmental concerns, and some guilt.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ruchit Garg, a Silicon Valley entrepreneur, says that he worries that something isn’t right with his Internet shopping habit. With each new delivery to his doorstep — sometimes several in a day — he faces the source of his guilt and frustration: another cardboard box.

headline.main: E-Commerce: Convenience Built on a Mountain of Cardboard

docs.abstract: Start-up funding isn’t as extravagant as it used to be, and some firms will not survive the downturn.
docs.snippet: Start-up funding isn’t as extravagant as it used to be, and some firms will not survive the downturn.
docs.lead_paragraph: Each Saturday, Farhad Manjoo and Mike Isaac, technology reporters at The New York Times, review the week’s news, offering analysis and maybe a joke or two about the most important developments in the tech industry.

headline.main: Farhad and Mike’s Week in Tech: Start-Ups and the Circle of Life

byline.original: By Farhad Manjoo and Mike Isaac

docs.abstract: Nielsen executives say that they have heard the complaints of TV and ad executives and are ready to track the many ways people consume media. But skeptics abound.
docs.snippet: Nielsen executives say that they have heard the complaints of TV and ad executives and are ready to track the many ways people consume media. But skeptics abound.
docs.lead_paragraph: Dennis Cheatham said he felt as if he were receiving a message from the past last May when a package arrived in the mail from Nielsen asking him to participate in the survey that for decades has detailed the television viewing habits of Americans.

headline.main: Nielsen Plays Catch-Up as Streaming Era Wreaks Havoc on TV Raters
headline.print_headline: Streaming Era Wreaks Havoc on TV Raters
